Solution:
The units digit of a page number depends only on its units digit.  Therefore, we only need to consider the units digit of each page number.  The units digit of the page numbers from 1 to 53 are shown below:

[asy]
unitsize(0.15 cm);

for(int i = 0; i <= 5; ++i) {
  draw((0,-2*i)--(53,-2*i));
}

for(int i = 0; i <= 53; ++i) {
  if (i % 10 == 0) {
    label(format("%d",i),(i,-10),S);
  } else {
    label(format("%d",i),(i,-2*floor(i/10)),S);
  }
}
[/asy]

The units digit of a page number is the same as the units digit of $53 - x + 1 = 54 - x,$ where $x$ is the original page number.  The units digit of $54 - x$ is the same as the units digit of $4 - x.$  Therefore, we seek the number of $x$ such that the units digit of $x$ is the same as the units digit of $4 - x.$

We list the possibilities below:

\begin{align*}
x &= 1 & 4 - x &= 3 \\
x &= 2 & 4 - x &= 2 \\
x &= 3 & 4 - x &= 5 \\
x &= 4 & 4 - x &= 0 \\
x &= 5 & 4 - x &= 9 \\
x &= 6 & 4 - x &= 8 \\
x &= 7 & 4 - x &= 7 \\
x &= 8 & 4 - x &= 6 \\
x &= 9 & 4 - x &= 9 \\
x &= 0 & 4 - x &= 4
\end{align*}

Therefore, the units digit of the page numbers from 1 to 53 and their reverses match in $\boxed{4}$ cases: 1 and 50, 2 and 40, 3 and 30, and 7 and 20.

